==Old English==

===Etymology===
Germanic ''*þarf-'', from Indo-European ''*terp-, *trep-''.
Germanic cognates include Old Frisian *[[thurva]], Old Saxon ''thurḅan'' (Dutch [[durven]]), Old Norse [[þurfa]] (Swedish [[tarfva]]), Old High German [[thurfan]] (German [[dürfen]]), Gothic *[[𐌸𐌰𐌿𐍂𐌱𐌰]].  The Indo-European root also led to Greek [[τερπειν]], Old Slavic [[trěbě]] (Russian [[требоватъ]]).

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /'θʊrfan/

===Verb===
'''þurfan''' (preterite-present)
# to [[need]], to be [[obliged]] (to do something).

